    "title": "Multicall reuses one `msg.value` across multiple payable delegatecalls, creating unbacked collateral and phantom balances",
    "locations": [
      "0xe4764f9cd8ecc9659d3abf35259638b20ac536e4/lib/openzeppelin-contracts/contracts/utils/Multicall.sol:17",
      "0xe4764f9cd8ecc9659d3abf35259638b20ac536e4/contracts/protocol/ParticleExchange.sol:201",
      "0xe4764f9cd8ecc9659d3abf35259638b20ac536e4/contracts/protocol/ParticleExchange.sol:214",
      "0xe4764f9cd8ecc9659d3abf35259638b20ac536e4/contracts/protocol/ParticleExchange.sol:466",
      "0xe4764f9cd8ecc9659d3abf35259638b20ac536e4/contracts/protocol/ParticleExchange.sol:569",
      "0xe4764f9cd8ecc9659d3abf35259638b20ac536e4/contracts/protocol/ParticleExchange.sol:650",
      "0xe4764f9cd8ecc9659d3abf35259638b20ac536e4/contracts/protocol/ParticleExchange.sol:685"
    ],
    "claim": "`Multicall.multicall()` delegatecalls into `ParticleExchange`, so every batched subcall observes the same original `msg.value`. The exchange's payable accounting treats `msg.value` as fresh deposit in each subcall (`swapWithEth`, `sellNftToMarket*`, `refinanceLoan`, `offerBid`, `updateBid`), allowing one ETH payment to back multiple independent state transitions.",
    "impact": "An attacker can open multiple loans or bids with only one actual deposit, then extract more ETH/NFT value than was funded. This creates direct bad debt against pooled collateral and can drain honest users' balances or lenders' protections.",
    "paths": [
      "Call `multicall([swapWithEth(lienA), swapWithEth(lienB)])` with `msg.value` equal to only one lien price; both delegatecalls treat the same ETH as newly deposited and release two NFTs / create two fully collateralized-looking loans.",
      "Call `multicall([offerBid(...), offerBid(...), cancelBid(...), cancelBid(...), withdrawAccountBalance()])` so the same ETH funds multiple bid margins and is later withdrawn multiple times."
    ]
  },
  {
