    "title": "Refinancing aliases the new lender's NFT into the old lien, allowing the old lender to steal the replacement collateral",
    "locations": [
      "0xe4764f9cd8ecc9659d3abf35259638b20ac536e4/contracts/protocol/ParticleExchange.sol:587",
      "0xe4764f9cd8ecc9659d3abf35259638b20ac536e4/contracts/protocol/ParticleExchange.sol:605",
      "0xe4764f9cd8ecc9659d3abf35259638b20ac536e4/contracts/protocol/ParticleExchange.sol:612",
      "0xe4764f9cd8ecc9659d3abf35259638b20ac536e4/contracts/protocol/ParticleExchange.sol:621",
      "0xe4764f9cd8ecc9659d3abf35259638b20ac536e4/contracts/protocol/ParticleExchange.sol:143"
    ],
    "claim": "During `refinanceLoan`, the old lien is converted back to an inactive lien but its `tokenId` is overwritten with `newLien.tokenId` while the new lien is also activated against that same `tokenId`. No NFT is moved, so two different liens now reference the single NFT supplied by the new lender.",
    "impact": "The old lender can immediately withdraw the new lender's NFT via `withdrawNft`, stealing the replacement collateral and leaving the new active loan completely unbacked. The new lender is left with pure counterparty exposure and likely unrecoverable loss.",
    "paths": [
      "Borrower refinances an active loan into another lender's inactive lien from the same collection.",
      "The protocol writes `oldLien.tokenId = newLien.tokenId` and `newLien.tokenId = newLien.tokenId` in parallel.",
      "The old lender calls `withdrawNft(oldLien, oldLienId)` and receives the new lender's NFT, while the new lien remains active and no longer has collateral behind it."
    ]
  },
